T1  - The Glass Cliff: Exploring the Dynamics Surrounding the Appointment of Women to Precarious Leadership Positions
AU  - Ryan, Michelle K.
AU  - Haslam, S. Alexander
Y1  - 2007/04/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2007.24351856
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2007.24351856
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 549
EP  - 572
VL  - 32
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this paper we explore the ?glass cliff? form of discrimination. We review archival and experimental evidence of the glass cliff and identify multiple processes as having the potential to contribute to the phenomenon. We also outline a range of potential reactions to the phenomenon, and we elaborate strategies for eliminating glass cliffs, but, as with other forms of (gender) discrimination, we argue that these depend on the capacity for disadvantaged groups to overcome resistance on the part of those who are motivated to maintain the status quo.
AB  - In this paper we explore the ?glass cliff? form of discrimination. We review archival and experimental evidence of the glass cliff and identify multiple processes as having the potential to contribute to the phenomenon. We also outline a range of potential reactions to the phenomenon, and we elaborate strategies for eliminating glass cliffs, but, as with other forms of (gender) discrimination, we argue that these depend on the capacity for disadvantaged groups to overcome resistance on the part of those who are motivated to maintain the status quo.
